-- #518, the OTHER direction: what must NOT default.  The #518 fix makes an impl
-- method body a Num-defaulting boundary; this pins the vars it must keep its hands
-- off, so a future widening of that boundary cannot pass the suite.
--
-- This fixture is not hypothetical — it FAILED during #518's own review.  The first
-- cut of the fix called `defaultGroupNum`, mirroring processLetGroup/processSCC.
-- That was wrong HERE, and this file is the shape that proves it: defaultGroupNum's
-- exclusion filter is `monoArgUnboundIds`, which walks only the DOMAINS of the
-- outermost arrow chain, so `b` in `lift : Num b => a -> Box b` (return position) got
-- ZERO protection and was ground to Int — permanently monomorphising a var the caller
-- had already fixed at Float.  MEASURED on real builds of both:
--   pre-#518            : MkBox 0.0   (correct)
--   #518 w/ defaultGroupNum : E-PANIC floatToString: not a Float   ← S0 traded for S0
--   #518 w/ defaultBodyLocalNum : MkBox 0.0   (correct — what ships)
-- The three arms below are each caller-determined through a DIFFERENT channel, which
-- is the point: an impl method's vars are not only fixed by arguments.
--   1. lift  — a METHOD-LEVEL constraint var (`Num b =>`) in RETURN position,
--              supplied by the method's own dict at the call site.  This is the arm
--              that regressed; it is invisible to any arg-position-only filter.
--   2. mk    — an IMPL-LEVEL `requires Num b` var, supplied by the impl's dict.
--   3. add2  — the ordinary arg-reachable var, at BOTH Int and Float.
-- Ground truth is the caller's annotation in every case (Box Float / Acc Float), not
-- whatever the binary prints.
data Box b = MkBox b deriving (Display)

data Acc b = MkAcc b deriving (Display)

interface Lift a where
  lift : Num b => a -> Box b

impl Lift Int where
  lift _ = MkBox 0

interface Mk a where
  mk : Unit -> a

impl Mk (Acc b) requires Num b where
  mk _ = MkAcc 0

interface Add2 a where
  add2 : a -> a -> a

impl Add2 Int where
  add2 x y = x + y + 0

impl Add2 Float where
  add2 x y = x + y + 0.0

q : Box Float
q = lift 3

z : Acc Float
z = mk ()

main =
  let _ = println q
  let _ = println z
  let _ = println (add2 1 2)
  println (add2 1.5 2.5)
